dlineExceeded`). Not wrapping these is correct — wrapping would obscure `errors.Is` checks upstream. The nolint comments with rationale are well done.\\n\\n### 4. Pager `context.Background()` comment is excellent\\n\\n`explain.go:1312-1316` — The comment explaining why `context.Background()` is used instead of the cancellable ctx is a model explanation. It documents a non-obvious decision that would otherwise invite \\\"helpful\\\" refactoring.\\n\\n### 5. Entry-point `ctx.Err()` checks are a good fast-fail pattern\\n\\nThe `_ = ctx` → `ctx.Err()` replacements in `committed.go` and `temporary.go` are a clean improvement. They fail fast before starting git tree traversals. Worth noting these are point-in-time checks only — the underlying `getSessionsBranchTree()` and similar methods don't accept `ctx`, so there's still a window where work proceeds after cancellation. That's fine as a pragmatic first step.\\n\\n### 6. Tests correctly use `context.Background()`\\n\\nAll test call sites pass `context.Background()`, which is the standard Go testing practice. No issues here.\\n\\n### 7. Minor: `runExplainBranchWithFilter` Ctrl+C handling\\n\\n`explain.go:1141-1146`:\\n\\n```go\\nif ctx.Err() != nil {\\n    return NewSilentError(ctx.Err())\\n}\\n```\\n\\nGood UX — Ctrl+C during branch loading exits cleanly instead of logging a warning. The `NewSilentError` wrapping fits the CLI's error handling pattern.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThe changes are well-scoped and consistently applied. The main actionable item is **#1** — `getAllChangedFilesBetweenTrees` returning `nil` on context cancellation leads to silently wrong attribution results. The rest are minor observations. The pager comment and the overall approach of checking `ctx.Err()` inside `ForEach` callbacks are both idiomatic Go.\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":2376,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":61507,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_